<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910103-0013</DOCNO><DOCID>910103-0013.</DOCID><HL>   Revco Case Marks Debut   For Court's Examiner</HL><DATE>01/03/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A8</SO><CO>   RDS</CO><IN>BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)DRUG-BASED RETAILERS AND WHOLESALERS, PHARMACIES (RTD)</IN><LP>   For Barry L. Zaretsky, the high-profile Revco caserepresents his debut as a court-appointed examiner.   However, Mr. Zaretsky, a Brooklyn Law School professor andcounsel to the 400-lawyer firm of Kelley Drye andamp; Warren, haswritten, lectured and consulted extensively on the topic ofleveraged buy-outs. He writes a regular bankruptcy column forthe New York Law Journal, a trade publication, and is theco-author of the monthly Commercial Law Report.</LP><TEXT>   Mr. Zaretsky, 40 years old, has been counsel to KelleyDrye since 1989 and a member of the faculty of Brooklyn LawSchool since 1978. He graduated from the University ofMichigan law school in 1974.   He says he and a team of Kelley Drye lawyers spenthundreds of hours interviewing most of the people involved inthe leveraged buy-out of Revco in an effort to unravel whatwent wrong. &quot;It was fascinating to delve into the structuringof an LBO,&quot; said Mr. Zaretsky. &quot;These are cutting edge legalissues that required a new approach.&quot;   As part of the investigation, the lawyers reviewed morethan 200,000 pages of documents about the LBO and the eventsafter the buy-out. In addition, Mr. Zaretsky researched thehistory of the 400-year-old fraudulent conveyance law and itsmost recent applications.</TEXT></DOC>